      <title>Re: Pathing Update</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&amp;message.id=13193#M13193</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Not only are the mobs still going back and forth several times before coming into camp, but snared mobs that have been pulled beyond group aggro range are not coming to the puller until they return to spawn &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;In Halls of Honor, The Nest, Akheva Ruins, Rift Seeker’s Sanctum, and spell missions Tak 1 and 69.2 (areas I have seen this over and over), snared mobs with aggro still wander back to spawn points before re-approaching the puller. By then, they have picked up all the mobs that the puller has been trying to split them from. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;This isn’t a plea for risk-free pulling – to split the snared mob, I am often timing a feign death to a second or less to draw the snared mob far enough away to be split. That has to be timed in the face of multiple heavy-hitting mobs sometimes approaching at a fast speed. It’s very frustrating to work a mob out with 2 or 3 of these feign pulls just to watch it meander back to the spawn point and bring friends. This usually happens on what should be the last feign &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The rooms in the Accused Nest are nearly unsplittable solo.&amp;nbsp; As soon as the snared mob is drawn out of aggro range of its mates, it returns to “tag up” at home base before proceeding after the puller. It’s not that I’ve lost agro, because as soon as it gets close every mob in the area comes running (and sometimes warping) to me. After touching its spawn point, the snared mob comes, too. It returns to the spawn point even if I land a spell on it as it walks back. I don’t have a problem with splitting being hard, and I don’t mind that I don’t shed aggro as easily as a monk or bard puller. What I have a problem with is after several near-death experiences to work a mob out of aggro range, the effort is wasted because the mob heads back to base instead of coming on the pull &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;These pathing problems are not limited to new or even newer zones.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
